course_code: CS101 | course_title: Introduction to Computer Science | department: Computer Science | credits: 3 | level: Beginner | prerequisites: None | description: Fundamental concepts in computer science including algorithms, data structures, and programming paradigms. Hands-on projects and problem-solving exercises. | instructor: Dr. Alice Johnson | semester_offered: Fall/Spring | capacity: 40 | meeting_times: MWF 9:00-10:00 AM, TTh 9:00-10:30 AM

course_code: CS201 | course_title: Data Structures and Algorithms | department: Computer Science | credits: 4 | level: Intermediate | prerequisites: CS101 | description: Advanced study of data structures (lists, trees, graphs), algorithm design, and computational complexity. Implementation in Python and C++. | instructor: Prof. Bob Chen | semester_offered: Spring | capacity: 35 | meeting_times: MWF 10:00-11:00 AM

course_code: CS301 | course_title: Artificial Intelligence | department: Computer Science | credits: 3 | level: Advanced | prerequisites: CS201 | description: Introduction to AI techniques: search algorithms, knowledge representation, machine learning basics, natural language processing. | instructor: Dr. Sarah Williams | semester_offered: Fall | capacity: 30 | meeting_times: TTh 13:00-14:30 (1:00-2:30 PM)

course_code: MATH101 | course_title: Calculus I | department: Mathematics | credits: 4 | level: Beginner | prerequisites: High School Algebra | description: Limits, derivatives, integrals of single-variable functions. Applications to optimization and physics problems. | instructor: Prof. Michael Smith | semester_offered: Fall/Spring | capacity: 50 | meeting_times: MWF 11:00-12:00 PM

course_code: MATH201 | course_title: Linear Algebra | department: Mathematics | credits: 3 | level: Intermediate | prerequisites: MATH101 | description: Vector spaces, matrices, eigenvalues, linear transformations, applications to systems and data analysis. | instructor: Dr. Jennifer Lee | semester_offered: Spring | capacity: 40 | meeting_times: TTh 10:00-11:30 AM

course_code: BIO101 | course_title: General Biology | department: Biology | credits: 4 | level: Beginner | prerequisites: None | description: Cell structure and function, genetics, evolution, ecology. Lab component includes microscopy and organism observations. | instructor: Prof. David Brown | semester_offered: Fall/Spring | capacity: 60 | meeting_times: MWF 13:00-14:00 (1:00-2:00 PM), Lab W 14:00-16:00

course_code: CHEM101 | course_title: General Chemistry | department: Chemistry | credits: 4 | level: Beginner | prerequisites: High School Chemistry | description: Atomic structure, bonding, stoichiometry, thermodynamics. Lab includes safety training and practical experiments. | instructor: Dr. Patricia Garcia | semester_offered: Fall/Spring | capacity: 45 | meeting_times: MWF 10:00-11:00 AM, Lab T 14:00-17:00

course_code: ENG101 | course_title: English Composition | department: English | credits: 3 | level: Beginner | prerequisites: None | description: Academic writing skills, essay structure, research methods, citation formats, peer review and revision. | instructor: Prof. Rebecca Martinez | semester_offered: Fall/Spring | capacity: 25 | meeting_times: MWF 14:00-15:00 (2:00-3:00 PM)

course_code: HIST101 | course_title: World History: Ancient to Medieval | department: History | credits: 3 | level: Beginner | prerequisites: None | description: Survey of major civilizations and events from prehistory through the Middle Ages. Emphasis on cultural and political development. | instructor: Dr. James Wilson | semester_offered: Fall | capacity: 35 | meeting_times: TTh 11:00-12:30 PM

# College Student Handbook ## 1. Academic Policies ### Course Registration and Add/Drop - Students must register during assigned registration window. Late registration permitted for fees. - Add/drop period: First 10 days of classes. After this, withdrawal with permission only. - Withdrawal grades (W) appear on transcript but do not affect GPA. - Maximum course load: 18 credits per semester. Minimum: 12 credits (full-time status). ### Grading System - A: 90-100%, A-: 87-89%, B+: 84-86%, B: 80-83%, B-: 77-79% - C+: 74-76%, C: 70-73%, C-: 67-69%, D: 60-66%, F: Below 60% - GPA calculated on 4.0 scale. S/U (Satisfactory/Unsatisfactory) option for up to 2 electives per year. - Grade appeals must be submitted within 7 days of grade posting. ### Academic Standing - Good standing: GPA >= 2.0 - Academic warning: GPA 1.5-2.0 (meeting required) - Academic probation: GPA < 1.5 (suspension possible) - Dean's List: GPA >= 3.5 (15+ credits completed) ### Attendance Policy - Students are expected to attend all classes. Extended absence (>3 classes) requires faculty notification. - Excused absences: Medical, family emergency, religious observance, college-approved travel. - Unexcused absences may result in grade reduction or course failure at instructor discretion. ## 2. Student Life and Conduct ### Code of Conduct - All students must adhere to the College Code of Conduct. - Prohibited behaviors: Cheating, plagiarism, harassment, violence, substance abuse, theft, property damage. - Violations may result in warnings, probation, suspension, or expulsion. ### Classroom Conduct - Disruptive behavior will result in removal from class. - Electronic devices (phones, laptops) permitted only if used for class purposes. - Respect for diversity and inclusion is mandatory. ### Housing Policies (On-Campus) - Housing required for first-year students (exceptions: commuter, married status). - Housing lottery for upper-class students held in March (announcement Dec 1). - Move-in: First day of semester. Move-out: Within 48 hours of final exam. - Guests limited to 3 consecutive nights in dorm rooms. ### Student Clubs and Organizations - 100+ clubs available covering academics, sports, arts, service, and identity. - Club meetings held in student center; contact Student Life for listings. - Funding available through Student Government (approval process required). ## 3. Support Services ### Academic Support - Writing Center: Free tutoring for papers, essays. Hours M-F 9am-5pm. - Math Lab: Peer tutoring for math courses. Hours TTh 10am-4pm, W 1pm-5pm. - Tutoring Services: One-on-one tutoring available for most subjects ($25/hr). ### Health and Wellness - Student Health Center: Primary care, vaccinations, mental health counseling. Hours M-F 8am-5pm. - Counseling Services: Free mental health counseling (8 sessions per year included). - Emergency: Use campus emergency line (ext. 911) or nearest emergency phone. - Wellness programs: Yoga, fitness classes, nutrition workshops (free for students). ### Accessibility Services - Students with disabilities: Register with Accessibility Services (ODS). - Accommodations available: Extended test time, note-taking, accessible housing, service animals permitted. - Contact: ods@college.edu or visit Accessibility Services Office (Student Center 200). ### Career Services - Resume reviews, interview coaching, internship placement assistance. - Career fairs held Fall (Sept)

Frequently Asked Questions **Q: What should I do if I need to withdraw from a course?** A: Contact the Registrar's Office. Withdrawals processed within the posted deadline receive a "W" grade. After the deadline, withdrawal requires academic dean approval (can impact financial aid). **Q: How do I request accommodations for a disability?** A: Register with Accessibility Services (ODS) with medical documentation. Contact ods@college.edu or visit Student Center 200. **Q: Can I change my major?** A: Yes, contact your academic advisor or the registrar. A major change form must be approved by your advisor and new department chair. **Q: What if I'm struggling academically?** A: Contact academic support (tutoring, writing center) or meet with your advisor. Probation students must see their advisor every 2 weeks. **Q: How do I appeal a grade?** A: Submit a written appeal to the faculty member within 7 days of grade posting. If unresolved, escalate to department chair, then academic dean. --- *Last Updated: June 2025* *For updates, visit college.edu/studenthandbook or contact Student Affairs at studentaffairs@college.edu*
